{"title_page": "Miele (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miele\n| image          = Miele (film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Valeria Golino]]\n| producer       = Viola Prestieri<br />[[Riccardo Scamarcio]]\n| writer         = Francesca Marciano<br>Valeria Golino<br />Valia Santella\n| based on       = novel 'A nome tuo'' by Mauro Covacich\n| starring       = [[Jasmine Trinca]]<br>[[Carlo Cecchi]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Gergely Poh\u00e1rnok\n| editing        = Giogi\u00f2 Franchini\n| distributor    = BIM Distribuzione (Italy)\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|5|1|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Miele''''' is a 2013 Italian [[drama film]] directed by [[Valeria Golino]]. It was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name=\"Cannes2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/59652.html |title=2013 Official Selection|date=20 April 2013|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=Cannes}}</ref> where it won a commendation from the Ecumenical Jury.<ref name=\"Variety-EJ\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/cannes-blue-is-the-warmest-color-wins-fipresci-prize-1200488042/ |title=Cannes: \u2018Blue Is the Warmest Color\u2019 Wins Fipresci Prize |date=26 May 2013|accessdate=26 May 2013|work=Variety}}</ref> It was also nominated for the 2013 [[Lux Prize]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jasmine Trinca]] as Irene/Miele\n* [[Carlo Cecchi]] as Carlo Grimaldi\n* [[Libero De Rienzo]] as Rocco\n* [[Vinicio Marchioni]] as Stefano\n* [[Iaia Forte]] as Clelia\n* [[Roberto De Francesco]] as Filippo\n* [[Barbara Ronchi]] as Sandra\n* [[Massimiliano Iacolucci]] as Irene's father\n* [[Claudio Guain]] as Ennio\n* [[Valeria Bilello]] as Irene's mother\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Anchor|Awards}}\n<!-- Please do not add awards or ceremonies that currently do not have a Wiki article. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=4 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | List of Accolades\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" width=\"40%\"| Award / Film Festival\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" width=\"30%\"| Category\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" width=\"25%\"| Recipient(s)\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" width=\"15%\"| Result\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Nastro d'Argento|67th Nastri d'Argento]]\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best New Director|Best New Director]]\n| Valeria Golino\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Producer|Best Producer]]\n| [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] and [[Viola Prestieri]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Jasmine Trinca]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Carlo Cecchi]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Giogi\u00f2 Franchini]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Sound|Best Sound]]\n| [[Emanuele Cecere]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[66th Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Un Certain Regard Award]]\n| [[Valeria Golino]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Prize of the Ecumenical Jury - Special Mention\n| Valeria Golino\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[David di Donatello|59th David di Donatello Awards]]\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best New Director|Best New Director]]\n| [[Valeria Golino]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Script|Best Script]]\n| [[Francesca Marciano]], [[Valia Santella]] & [[Valeria Golino]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Producer|Best Producer]]\n| [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] and [[Viola Prestieri]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Carlo Cecchi]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Jasmine Trinca]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Gergely Poharnok]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[David di Donatello for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Giogi\u00f2 Franchini]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Globo d'oro|53rd Italian Golden Globe]]\n|-\n| [[Globo d'oro|Best First Feature]]\n| Valeria Golino\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Globo d'oro|Best Actress]]\n| [[Jasmine Trinca]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2357461|Miele}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miele}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about euthanasia]]\n{{2010s-Italy-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miele\n| image          = Miele (film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Valeria Golino]]\n| producer       = Viola Prestieri<br />[[Riccardo Scamarcio]]\n| writer         = Francesca Marciano<br>Valeria Golino<br />Valia Santella\n| based on       = novel 'A nome tuo'' by Mauro Covacich\n| starring       = [[Jasmine Trinca]]<br>[[Carlo Cecchi]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Gergely Poh\u00e1rnok\n| editing        = Giogi\u00f2 Franchini\n| distributor    = BIM Distribuzione (Italy)\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|5|1|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Miele''''' is a 2013 Italian [[drama film]] directed by [[Valeria Golino]]. It was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name=\"Cannes2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/59652.html |title=2013 Official Selection|date=20 April 2013|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=Cannes}}</ref> where it won a commendation from the Ecumenical Jury.<ref name=\"Variety-EJ\">{{cite web|u