{"title_page": "Jhulelal (Hinduism)", "text_new": "{{short description|Incarnation of Varuna}}\n{{about|the Hindu deity|the Muslim mystic|Jhulelal (Sufism)}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| image       = Jhulelal hindu deity.jpg\n| caption     =Jhulelal sitting on a lotus flower in the middle of a river and surrounded by a couple of silver fish (palla fish)\n| name        = Jhulelal\n| affiliation = [[Varuna]] [[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]] \n| mantra      = \n| weapon      = Sword\n| siblings  = Arhastra \n| consort     =\n| abode       = Sea & River [[Indus]]\n| mount       = Fish & Horse\n}}\n{{Hinduism}}\n\n'''Jhulelal''' is a name that refers to the ''[[I\u1e63\u1e6da-devat\u0101|Ishta Dev]]'' (most-revered deity) of [[Sindhi Hindus]], who regard him to be an incarnation of the [[Hindu]] deity [[Varuna]].<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\">[http://www.jhulelal.com/infotainment/story.html Story of Jhulelal] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.jhulelal.com/infotainment/story.html&date=2011-05-01 |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref><ref>http://www.sanskritimagazine.com/indian-religions/hinduism/supernatural-nature-sindhi-tradition/</ref> The chant ''Jhule Lal Jhule Lal'' is considered the \"clarion call\" of Sindhi Hindus.<ref name=lari>{{cite book|last1=Lari|first1=Suhail Zaheer|title=A history of Sindh|date=1994|publisher=Oxford|isbn=0195775015|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LfFtAAAAMAAJ&dq=sukkur+sindh&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=sukkur|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>His birth name was '''Uderolal''' (colloquially called '''Oderolal'''). It is said that the when Uderolal was a child, his cradle (swing) rocked itself to lull him to sleep, earning him the name Jhulelal - The Lord of the Swing<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\nJhulelal is traditionally believed to have performed several miracles, typically centred around the [[Indus River]] \u2013 which Hindus consider to be his abode.<ref name=lari/> Sindhi Hindus worship Jhulelal at the [[Shrine at Odero Lal]] in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Sindh]] province, which is jointly used by Hindus, and Sindhi Muslims who revere the shrine as the tomb of Sheikh Tahir. A second shrine named ''Jhulelal Tirthdham'' exists in [[India]] at [[Narayan Sarovar]], [[Kutch]], [[Gujarat]].<ref name=Tirthdham1/>\n \nHe is represented as a man with a flowing white beard, sitting on a lotus flower in the middle of a river and surrounded by a couple of silver fish (palla fish).<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1227241</ref> It is said that when the boy was born, he revealed his divine identity to his father Rattanchand and his mother Devaki. When he opened his mouth, his parents saw-the mighty Sindhu river flowing and an old man seated on a pala fish(a large salmon indigenous to the Sindhu river).<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Jhulelal.jpg|thumb]]\nJhulelal is the ''[[I\u1e63\u1e6da-devat\u0101|Ishta Dev]]'' (preferred God) of [[Sindhi Hindus|Sindhi  people]].<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\"/> Jhulelal continues to be the unifying force and the centre of all cultural activities of the Sindhi community. When Sindhi men venture out to sea, their women pray to Jhulelal for their safe return.  They offer the Lord a [[prasad]] of akha, a sweet made from rice, ghee, sugar and flour.  Sindhis all over the world greet each other with the words, \"Jaiko chawando Jhulelal thenja thinde Beda-Paar\".\n\nAlthough the exact time and year of Jhulelal's incarnation is not known, his birth year is estimated sometime in the middle of the 10th Century. It is widely believed among the Sindhis that the Water God incarnated as Jhulelal.\n\nAccording to tradition, a tyrannical ruler named Mirkh Shah from nearby [[Thatta]] ordered that local Sindhis to convert into Islam within 24 hours or sacrifice. Local Sindhis, fearful of this edict, prayed at the banks of the [[Indus River]], where they then saw a vision of the Sindhis deity [[Varuna]] who informed the worshippers that he would re-incarnate himself as an infant to be born in [[Nasirpur]] in order to deliver them from their hardships.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=The Supernatural in Nature of the Sindhi Tradition|url=http://www.sanskritimagazine.com/indian-religions/hinduism/supernatural-nature-sindhi-tradition/|publisher=Sanskriti Magazine|accessdate=4 March 2017|date=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nJhulelal was born on the first day of the Hindu month of [[Chaitra]].This day is celebrated by Sindhi Hindus as [[Cheti Chand]].<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/><ref name=falzon159/><ref name=kumar120>{{cite book|author=P. Pratap Kumar|title=Contemporary Hinduism|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7Wd_BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120|year= 2014|publisher= Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-54636-8|pages= 120\u2013124}}</ref>  Upon hearing of the infant's birth, Mirkhshah commanded his minister Ahirio to kill the infant with a poisoned rose petal. When Ahirio saw the infant, Jhulelal smiled and the poisoned rose petal blew out of Ahirio's possession. When Ahirio caught sight of Jhulelal for a second time, he was startled to see that the infant had grown into an elderly man. The elderly man was then said to have turned into a young man, and then a warrior on horseback before Ahirio's eyes.<ref name=\"Westland\">{{cite book|last1=Bhavnani |first1=Nandita |title=The Making of Exile: Sindhi Sindhis and the Partition of India|date=2014|publisher=Westland|isbn=9789384030339}}</ref>\n\nAhirio returned to recount the story to Mirkhshah, who then lambasted Ahirio, and told him to leave and call out for Jhulelal by the banks of the Indus.  Upon calling for Jhulelal, the warrior on horseback appeared out of the river to appear to Ahirio with an accompanying army. Terrified, Ahirio begged Jhulelal to restrain his army. Jhulelal's army then disappeared back into the River Indus, while Ahirio went back to the palace to recount the story to Mirkhshah. Mirkhshah remained skeptical, but invited Jhulelal to his court. Jhulelal is then said to have vanished, leaving Mirkhshah enraged. Jhulelal's followers then rushed to the house in [[Nasarpur]] where Jhulelal was born, and found Jhulelal there as an infant. The infant consoled the distraught Sindhis and commanded them to assemble at a temple near the Indus River. Upon assembling, a firestorm broke out and engulfed Mirkhshah's palaces. The king escaped to the banks of the river, where he found Jhulelal, now again a warrior, and his Sindhi followers protected from the firestorm. The kings fell at Jhulelal's feet, and Jhulelal dismissed the storm with the movement of his hand.<ref name=\"Westland\"/>After saving the Sindhis, it is believed that he was swallowed up by the earth.A temple was built at this point ,which is now called the [[Shrine at Odero Lal|oderolal shrine]].<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\nJhulelal is also believed by SindhiSindhis to have performed miracles, such as entering the Indus river at Nasirpur, and coming up at [[Bukkur]], at the northernmost extent of Sindh.<ref name=\"lari\"/>\n\n==Festivals==\n{{main|Cheti Chand|Chalio}}\n\n===Cheti Chand===\nThe [[Cheti Chand]] festival in the Hindu month of [[Chaitra]] marks the arrival of spring and harvest, but in Sindhi Hindu community, it also marks the mythical birth of Uderolal in the year 1007.<ref name=falzon159/><ref name=kumar120>{{cite book|author=P. Pratap Kumar|title=Contemporary Hinduism|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7Wd_BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120|year= 2014|publisher= Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-54636-8|pages= 120\u2013124}}</ref><ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\">{{cite book|author=S. Ramey|title=Hindu, Sufi, or Sikh: Contested Practices and Identifications of Sindhi Hindus in India and Beyond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bv2ADAAAQBAJ|year=2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-61622-6|pages=8, 36}}</ref> Uderolal morphed into a warrior and old man who preached and reprimanded Mirkhshah that Muslims and Hindus deserve the same religious freedoms. He, as Jhulelal,<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/> became the saviour of the Sindhi Hindus, who according to this legend, celebrate the new year as Uderolal's birthday.<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/><ref name=falzon159>{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA59|year=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-14008-5|pages=58\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===Chaliya saheb===\n[[Chalio]] or Chaliho, also called Chaliho Sahib, is a forty-day-long festival celebrated by Sindhi Hindus<ref name=a>[http://www.festivalsofindia.in/Chaliho/ Chaliho festival] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916224736/http://www.festivalsofindia.in/Chaliho/ |date=September 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=b>[http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/MAH-PUN-sindhis-celebrate-chalio-festival-2272672.html Sindhis celebrate Chalio festival]</ref><ref name=d>[http://www.thesindhuworld.com/chaliho.html Sindhi Festivals > Chaliho] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425020539/http://www.thesindhuworld.com/chaliho.html |date=April 25, 2012 }}</ref> to express their gratitude to Jhulelal for saving them from their impending conversion to Islam. The 40-day-long festival is observed every year in months of July to August, dates vary according to [[Hindu calendar]].<ref name=a/><ref name=b/> It is a thanksgiving celebration in honor of Varuna Deva for listening to their prayers.<ref name=a/><ref name=b/>\n\n==Odero Lal Shrine==\n[[File:OL 1.jpg|thumb|Odero Lal Shrine]]\nIt is believed that after saving the Sindhi Hindus, Jhulelal or Oderolal was swallowed up by the earth. A Shrine was built at this point ,which is now called the [[Shrine at Odero Lal|oderolal shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Jhulelal [[Shrine at Odero Lal]] is situated in [[Matiari District]], almost 40 kilometers away from the [[Sanghar District]] of [[Sindh]]; The Hindus and the Muslims can pray here at the same place simultaneously.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zahida Rehman Jatt|title=Jhulay Lal's cradle of tolerance|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1185942|accessdate=22 December 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn|date=June 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Claude Markovits|title=The Global World of Indian Merchants, 1750\u20131947: Traders of Sind from Bukhara to Panama|publisher=Cambridge University Press, 2000|isbn=9781139431279|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M2vu7Odjz6kC&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=Udero+Lal+town&source=bl&ots=GY7SzhBLva&sig=c0PrI6JIHCr52hKb1vohFe8_ahM&hl=sd&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Udero%20Lal%20town&f=false|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> [[Nawabshah]], [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Matiari]], [[Sanghar]] and [[Mirpur Khas]] are the nearby major cities to reach at the Shrine near [[Tando Adam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Cities near Udero L\u0101l in Sindh, Pakistan|url=http://www.gomapper.com/travel/list-of-cities-near/udero-lal.html|website=GoMapper|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt forms the seat of the Daryapanthis, originally a sub-sect of the followers of [[Gorakhnath]], who belong to the [[Nath]] tradition.<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1318886|title=How this lesser known festival is celebrated annually by Hindus in Sindh|last=Jatt|first=Zahida Rehman|date=2017-03-07|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Jhulelal Tirthdham==\n[[Sindhi Hindus]] in India built a religious shrine and cultural complex in [[Kutch]], near the border of [[Sindh Province]].<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1>{{cite web|title=Coming up in Gujarat, Sindhis' own sacred shrine - Times of India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coming-up-in-gujarat-sindhis-own-sacred-shrine/articleshow/69287901.cms|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref> The 100-acre complex includes 100-feet statue of Lord Jhulelal, a museum, meditation centre, an auditorium, cultural and arts-crafts centre with 100 accommodations.<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1/> Aiming to be the ''\"a centre for global Sindhi identity\"''<ref name=Tirthdham1/> the project costs estimated \u20b9100 crore and was built on donation of wealthy Indian Sindhis.<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1/> [[Harish Fabiani]] one of key promoter of the project stated regarding the cultural complex  ''\"The younger generation is aware they are Sindhis, but they do not know their language. We must learn our language and culture. We should have a place we can call our own.\"''<ref name=Tirthdham>{{cite web|last1= Shradha Shahani|title=Sindhis are building a Jhulelal Tirthdham\u2014their own holy city|url=https://www.cntraveller.in/story/sindhis-are-building-a-jhulelal-tirthdham-their-own-holy-city/|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Slogan of Jhulelal==\nJeko chawundo Jhule Lal Tehnija Theenda Bera Paar (\u062c\u064a\u06aa\u0648 \u0686\u0648\u0646\u062f\u0648 \u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0627\u0644 \u060c \u062a\u064e\u0646\u0647\u0646 \u062c\u0627 \u067f\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0627 \u067b\u064a\u0699\u0627 \u067e\u0627\u0631)\u2019 meaning whoever says Jhule Lal his/her ship will reach the shores (safely).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parveen Talpur|title=Fish Symbol: Indus Civilization to Biblical References|url=http://parveentalpur.com/2012/12/25/fish-symbol-indus-civilization-to-biblical-references/|website=parveentalpur.com|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Iconography===\n* In the most common form, Jhulelal is represented as a bearded man sitting cross-legged on a [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus flower]] that rests on a [[Tenualosa ilisha|palla fish]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nadeem F. Paracha|title=Jhulay Lal's full circle|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1227241/jhulay-lals-full-circle|accessdate=22 December 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn|date=December 20, 2015}}</ref> The fish is seen floating on the Sindhu river. He holds a sacred text and sometimes even a rosary. He wears a golden crown with a [[peacock]] feather and wears regal clothes. Generally, temple idols represent him in this form.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC|accessdate=1 February 2014|volume=9|year=2004|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|isbn=90-04-14008-5|page=59}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Boivin|first=Michel|date=15 Oct 2008|page=76|title=Sindh through History and Representations: French Contributions to Sindhi Studies|url=|location=|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195475036}}</ref>\n* In another form, he is shown standing on a palla fish or the lotus flower, holding a staff with both hands to indicate leadership.<ref name=\"cosmopolitan connections sindhi diaspora\">{{cite book | title=Cosmopolitan Connections:The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000 (International Comparative Social Studies, Vol. 9)| last=Falzon| first=Mark-Anthony| year=2004| pages=59| publisher=Brill Academic Publishers| id=9789004140080}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cheti Chand]]\n*[[Shri Varun Dev Mandir]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thesindhuworld.com All About Sindhis]\n* [http://www.jhulelal.com Jhule Lal]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120819084643/http://www.thesindhuworld.com/jhulelal.html Sindhi Deity Jhulelal]\n\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Regional Hindu gods]]\n[[Category:Hindu folk deities]]\n[[Category:Hinduism in Sindh]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Hindu saints]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Incarnation of Varuna}}\n{{about|the Hindu deity|the Muslim mystic|Jhulelal (Sufism)}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| image       = Jhulelal hindu deity.jpg\n| caption     =Jhulelal sitting on a lotus flower in the middle of a river and surrounded by a couple of silver fish (palla fish)\n| name        = Jhulelal\n| affiliation = [[Varuna]] [[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]] \n| mantra      = \n| weapon      = Sword\n| siblings  = Arhastra \n| consort     =\n| abode       = Sea & River [[Indus]]\n| mount       = Fish & Horse\n}}\n{{Hinduism}}\n\n'''Jhulelal''' is a name that refers to the ''[[I\u1e63\u1e6da-devat\u0101|Ishta Dev]]'' (most-revered deity) of [[Sindhi Hindus]], who regard him to be an incarnation of the [[Hindu]] deity [[Varuna]].<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\">[http://www.jhulelal.com/infotainment/story.html Story of Jhulelal] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.jhulelal.com/infotainment/story.html&date=2011-05-01 |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref><ref>http://www.sanskritimagazine.com/indian-religions/hinduism/supernatural-nature-sindhi-tradition/</ref> The chant ''Jhule Lal Jhule Lal'' is considered the \"clarion call\" of Sindhi Hindus.<ref name=lari>{{cite book|last1=Lari|first1=Suhail Zaheer|title=A history of Sindh|date=1994|publisher=Oxford|isbn=0195775015|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LfFtAAAAMAAJ&dq=sukkur+sindh&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=sukkur|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>His birth name was '''Uderolal''' (colloquially called '''Oderolal'''). It is said that the when Uderolal was a child, his cradle (swing) rocked itself to lull him to sleep, earning him the name Jhulelal - The Lord of the Swing<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\nJhulelal is traditionally believed to have performed several miracles, typically centred around the [[Indus River]] \u2013 which Hindus consider to be his abode.<ref name=lari/> Sindhi Hindus worship Jhulelal at the [[Shrine at Odero Lal]] in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Sindh]] province, which is jointly used by Hindus, and Sindhi Muslims who revere the shrine as the tomb of Sheikh Tahir. A second shrine named ''Jhulelal Tirthdham'' exists in [[India]] at [[Narayan Sarovar]], [[Kutch]], [[Gujarat]].<ref name=Tirthdham1/>\n \nHe is represented as a man with a flowing white beard, sitting on a lotus flower in the middle of a river and surrounded by a couple of silver fish (palla fish).<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1227241</ref> It is said that when the boy was born, he revealed his divine identity to his father Rattanchand and his mother Devaki. When he opened his mouth, his parents saw-the mighty Sindhu river flowing and an old man seated on a pala fish(a large salmon indigenous to the Sindhu river).<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Jhulelal.jpg|thumb]]\nJhulelal is the ''[[I\u1e63\u1e6da-devat\u0101|Ishta Dev]]'' (preferred God) of [[Sindhi Hindus|Sindhi  people]].<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\"/> Jhulelal continues to be the unifying force and the centre of all cultural activities of the Sindhi community. When Sindhi men venture out to sea, their women pray to Jhulelal for their safe return.  They offer the Lord a [[prasad]] of akha, a sweet made from rice, ghee, sugar and flour.  Sindhis all over the world greet each other with the words, \"Jaiko chawando Jhulelal thenja thinde Beda-Paar\".\n\nAlthough the exact time and year of Jhulelal's incarnation is not known, his birth year is estimated sometime in the middle of the 10th Century. It is widely believed among the Sindhis that the Water God incarnated as Jhulelal.\n\nAccording to tradition, a tyrannical ruler named Mirkh Shah from nearby [[Thatta]] ordered that local Sindhis to convert into Islam within 24 hours or sacrifice. Local Sindhis, fearful of this edict, prayed at the banks of the [[Indus River]], where they then saw a vision of the Sindhis deity [[Varuna]] who informed the worshippers that he would re-incarnate himself as an infant to be born in [[Nasirpur]] in order to deliver them from their hardships.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=The Supernatural in Nature of the Sindhi Tradition|url=http://www.sanskritimagazine.com/indian-religions/hinduism/supernatural-nature-sindhi-tradition/|publisher=Sanskriti Magazine|accessdate=4 March 2017|date=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nJhulelal was born on the first day of the Hindu month of [[Chaitra]]..This day is celebrated by Sindhi Hindus as [[Cheti Chand]].<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/><ref name=falzon159/><ref name=kumar120>{{cite book|author=P. Pratap Kumar|title=Contemporary Hinduism|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7Wd_BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120|year= 2014|publisher= Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-54636-8|pages= 120\u2013124}}</ref>  Upon hearing of the infant's birth, Mirkhshah commanded his minister Ahirio to kill the infant with a poisoned rose petal. When Ahirio saw the infant, Jhulelal smiled and the poisoned rose petal blew out of Ahirio's possession. When Ahirio caught sight of Jhulelal for a second time, he was startled to see that the infant had grown into an elderly man. The elderly man was then said to have turned into a young man, and then a warrior on horseback before Ahirio's eyes.<ref name=\"Westland\">{{cite book|last1=Bhavnani |first1=Nandita |title=The Making of Exile: Sindhi Sindhis and the Partition of India|date=2014|publisher=Westland|isbn=9789384030339}}</ref>\n\nAhirio returned to recount the story to Mirkhshah, who then lambasted Ahirio, and told him to leave and call out for Jhulelal by the banks of the Indus.  Upon calling for Jhulelal, the warrior on horseback appeared out of the river to appear to Ahirio with an accompanying army. Terrified, Ahirio begged Jhulelal to restrain his army. Jhulelal's army then disappeared back into the River Indus, while Ahirio went back to the palace to recount the story to Mirkhshah. Mirkhshah remained skeptical, but invited Jhulelal to his court. Jhulelal is then said to have vanished, leaving Mirkhshah enraged. Jhulelal's followers then rushed to the house in [[Nasarpur]] where Jhulelal was born, and found Jhulelal there as an infant. The infant consoled the distraught Sindhis and commanded them to assemble at a temple near the Indus River. Upon assembling, a firestorm broke out and engulfed Mirkhshah's palaces. The king escaped to the banks of the river, where he found Jhulelal, now again a warrior, and his Sindhi followers protected from the firestorm. The kings fell at Jhulelal's feet, and Jhulelal dismissed the storm with the movement of his hand.<ref name=\"Westland\"/>After saving the Sindhis, it is believed that he was swallowed up by the earth.A temple was built at this point ,which is now called the oderolal shrine.<ref>https://www.livehistoryindia.com/snapshort-histories/2017/07/14/jhulelal-the-god-of-the-indus</ref>\n\nJhulelal is also believed by SindhiSindhis to have performed miracles, such as entering the Indus river at Nasirpur, and coming up at [[Bukkur]], at the northernmost extent of Sindh.<ref name=\"lari\"/>\n\n==Festivals==\n{{main|Cheti Chand|Chalio}}\n\n===Cheti Chand===\nThe [[Cheti Chand]] festival in the Hindu month of [[Chaitra]] marks the arrival of spring and harvest, but in Sindhi Hindu community, it also marks the mythical birth of Uderolal in the year 1007.<ref name=falzon159/><ref name=kumar120>{{cite book|author=P. Pratap Kumar|title=Contemporary Hinduism|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7Wd_BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120|year= 2014|publisher= Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-54636-8|pages= 120\u2013124}}</ref><ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\">{{cite book|author=S. Ramey|title=Hindu, Sufi, or Sikh: Contested Practices and Identifications of Sindhi Hindus in India and Beyond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bv2ADAAAQBAJ|year=2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-61622-6|pages=8, 36}}</ref> Uderolal morphed into a warrior and old man who preached and reprimanded Mirkhshah that Muslims and Hindus deserve the same religious freedoms. He, as Jhulelal,<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/> became the saviour of the Sindhi Hindus, who according to this legend, celebrate the new year as Uderolal's birthday.<ref name=\"Ramey2008p8\"/><ref name=falzon159>{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA59|year=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-14008-5|pages=58\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===Chaliya saheb===\n[[Chalio]] or Chaliho, also called Chaliho Sahib, is a forty-day-long festival celebrated by Sindhi Hindus<ref name=a>[http://www.festivalsofindia.in/Chaliho/ Chaliho festival] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916224736/http://www.festivalsofindia.in/Chaliho/ |date=September 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=b>[http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/MAH-PUN-sindhis-celebrate-chalio-festival-2272672.html Sindhis celebrate Chalio festival]</ref><ref name=d>[http://www.thesindhuworld.com/chaliho.html Sindhi Festivals > Chaliho] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425020539/http://www.thesindhuworld.com/chaliho.html |date=April 25, 2012 }}</ref> to express their gratitude to Jhulelal for saving them from their impending conversion to Islam. The 40-day-long festival is observed every year in months of July to August, dates vary according to [[Hindu calendar]].<ref name=a/><ref name=b/> It is a thanksgiving celebration in honor of Varuna Deva for listening to their prayers.<ref name=a/><ref name=b/>\n\n==Odero Lal Shrine==\n[[File:OL 1.jpg|thumb|Odero Lal Shrine]]\nThe Jhulelal [[Shrine at Odero Lal]] is situated in [[Matiari District]], almost 40 kilometers away from the [[Sanghar District]] of [[Sindh]]; The Hindus and the Muslims can pray here at the same place simultaneously.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zahida Rehman Jatt|title=Jhulay Lal's cradle of tolerance|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1185942|accessdate=22 December 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn|date=June 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Claude Markovits|title=The Global World of Indian Merchants, 1750\u20131947: Traders of Sind from Bukhara to Panama|publisher=Cambridge University Press, 2000|isbn=9781139431279|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M2vu7Odjz6kC&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=Udero+Lal+town&source=bl&ots=GY7SzhBLva&sig=c0PrI6JIHCr52hKb1vohFe8_ahM&hl=sd&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Udero%20Lal%20town&f=false|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> [[Nawabshah]], [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Matiari]], [[Sanghar]] and [[Mirpur Khas]] are the nearby major cities to reach at the Shrine near [[Tando Adam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Cities near Udero L\u0101l in Sindh, Pakistan|url=http://www.gomapper.com/travel/list-of-cities-near/udero-lal.html|website=GoMapper|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt forms the seat of the Daryapanthis, originally a sub-sect of the followers of [[Gorakhnath]], who belong to the [[Nath]] tradition.<ref name=\"Story of Jhulelal\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1318886|title=How this lesser known festival is celebrated annually by Hindus in Sindh|last=Jatt|first=Zahida Rehman|date=2017-03-07|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Jhulelal Tirthdham==\n[[Sindhi Hindus]] in India built a religious shrine and cultural complex in [[Kutch]], near the border of [[Sindh Province]].<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1>{{cite web|title=Coming up in Gujarat, Sindhis' own sacred shrine - Times of India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coming-up-in-gujarat-sindhis-own-sacred-shrine/articleshow/69287901.cms|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref> The 100-acre complex includes 100-feet statue of Lord Jhulelal, a museum, meditation centre, an auditorium, cultural and arts-crafts centre with 100 accommodations.<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1/> Aiming to be the ''\"a centre for global Sindhi identity\"''<ref name=Tirthdham1/> the project costs estimated \u20b9100 crore and was built on donation of wealthy Indian Sindhis.<ref name=Tirthdham/><ref name=Tirthdham1/> [[Harish Fabiani]] one of key promoter of the project stated regarding the cultural complex  ''\"The younger generation is aware they are Sindhis, but they do not know their language. We must learn our language and culture. We should have a place we can call our own.\"''<ref name=Tirthdham>{{cite web|last1= Shradha Shahani|title=Sindhis are building a Jhulelal Tirthdham\u2014their own holy city|url=https://www.cntraveller.in/story/sindhis-are-building-a-jhulelal-tirthdham-their-own-holy-city/|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Slogan of Jhulelal==\nJeko chawundo Jhule Lal Tehnija Theenda Bera Paar (\u062c\u064a\u06aa\u0648 \u0686\u0648\u0646\u062f\u0648 \u062c\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0627\u0644 \u060c \u062a\u064e\u0646\u0647\u0646 \u062c\u0627 \u067f\u064a\u0646\u062f\u0627 \u067b\u064a\u0699\u0627 \u067e\u0627\u0631)\u2019 meaning whoever says Jhule Lal his/her ship will reach the shores (safely).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parveen Talpur|title=Fish Symbol: Indus Civilization to Biblical References|url=http://parveentalpur.com/2012/12/25/fish-symbol-indus-civilization-to-biblical-references/|website=parveentalpur.com|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Iconography===\n* In the most common form, Jhulelal is represented as a bearded man sitting cross-legged on a [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus flower]] that rests on a [[Tenualosa ilisha|palla fish]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nadeem F. Paracha|title=Jhulay Lal's full circle|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1227241/jhulay-lals-full-circle|accessdate=22 December 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn|date=December 20, 2015}}</ref> The fish is seen floating on the Sindhu river. He holds a sacred text and sometimes even a rosary. He wears a golden crown with a [[peacock]] feather and wears regal clothes. Generally, temple idols represent him in this form.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mark-Anthony Falzon|title=Cosmopolitan Connections: The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC|accessdate=1 February 2014|volume=9|year=2004|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|isbn=90-04-14008-5|page=59}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Boivin|first=Michel|date=15 Oct 2008|page=76|title=Sindh through History and Representations: French Contributions to Sindhi Studies|url=|location=|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195475036}}</ref>\n* In another form, he is shown standing on a palla fish or the lotus flower, holding a staff with both hands to indicate leadership.<ref name=\"cosmopolitan connections sindhi diaspora\">{{cite book | title=Cosmopolitan Connections:The Sindhi Diaspora, 1860\u20132000 (International Comparative Social Studies, Vol. 9)| last=Falzon| first=Mark-Anthony| year=2004| pages=59| publisher=Brill Academic Publishers| id=9789004140080}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cheti Chand]]\n*[[Shri Varun Dev Mandir]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thesindhuworld.com All About Sindhis]\n* [http://www.jhulelal.com Jhule Lal]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120819084643/http://www.thesindhuworld.com/jhulelal.html Sindhi Deity Jhulelal]\n\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Regional Hindu gods]]\n[[Category:Hindu folk deities]]\n[[Category:Hinduism in Sindh]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Hindu saints]]\n", "name_user": "Missbaloch", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOdero Lal Shrine)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jhulelal_(Hinduism)"}
{"title_page": "London Underground C69 and C77 Stock", "text_new": "{{Infobox train\n|name         = London Underground C69 and C77 Stock\n|image        = High Street Kensington. 5730.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|caption      = A refurbished C Stock at [[High Street Kensington tube station|High Street Kensington]]\n|interiorimage = C Stock DM Interior.jpg\n|interiorcaption = The interior of refurbished C Stock\n|manufacturer = [[Metro-Cammell]]<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\">{{cite web|title=Rolling Stock Data Sheet, London Underground (First Edition)|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/66598/response/170252/attach/4/Rolling%20stock%20Data%20Sheet%202nd%20Edition%201.pdf|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n|factory      = [[Washwood Heath]], [[England]]<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n|service      = 28 September 1970 \u2013 29 June 2014 \n|family       =\n|refurbishment = 1991\u20131994\n|replaced     = [[London Underground O and P Stock|O and P Stock]]\n|lines        = {{ubl|[[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] (1970\u20132014)|[[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] (1970\u20132014)|[[District line|District]] ([[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]]\u2013[[Edgware Road tube station (Circle, District and Hammersmith & City lines)|Edgware Road]]) (1978\u20132014)}}\n|formation    = 2 cars per unit, 3 units per train\n|carlength    = DM {{convert|16.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<br>T {{convert|14.94|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|carbody      = Aluminium\n|trainlength  =\n|width        = {{convert|2.92|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|3.68|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|traction     = Pneumatically driven double camshaft<br>(C69: [[GEC Traction|English Electric-AEI Traction]]<br>C77: [[GEC Traction]])<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n|traction motors = LT117 DC motor<br>([[Brush Traction]])<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n| collectionmethod = [[Contact shoe]]\n|maxspeed     =\n|weight       = DM {{convert|31.70|t|LT ST|abbr=on}}<br>T {{convert|20.2|t|LT ST|abbr=on}}\n|seating      = 198 per trainset\n|capacity     = 821 per trainset\n|stocktype    = [[London Underground infrastructure#Subsurface versus deep-level tube lines|Subsurface]]\n|notes        = \n}}\n\nThe '''London Underground C69 and C77 Stock''', commonly referred to as '''C Stock''', was a type of sub-surface rolling stock used on the [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]], [[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] and [[District line|District]] lines of the [[London Underground]] between 1970 and 2014.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1968, '''C69''' stock 6-car trains were ordered from [[Metro-Cammell]] of [[Washwood Heath]] to replace [[London Underground O and P Stock|O Stock and P Stock]] on [[London Underground]]'s [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] and [[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] lines for delivery from 1969, but trials of a four-car unit were delayed until summer 1970.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=114}} The first entered service on 28 September 1970.<ref name=Hardy>{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=Brian|title=London Underground Rolling Stock|date=1997|publisher=Capital Transport|location=Harrow|isbn=185414 193 7|pages=44\u201346|edition=14}}</ref>\n\nThe C69 stock was constructed using the then-standard form of a load-bearing aluminium underframe with a non-load-bearing body of riveted panels on aluminium framing. The high-density nature of the Circle line service meant that loading times were important; consequently all cars were fitted with four double sets of air-operated sliding doors per side. Seating was mainly transverse, and total seating capacity was 32 per car. The 106 DM cars (Nos 5501-5606) were each coupled to one of 106 T (Nos 6501-6606) forming semi-permanent two-car units, with an automatic coupler at each end. Three such units were then marshalled as six-car trains for normal service. The DM cars were slightly longer to accommodate the drivers' cabs, the saloon dimensions in all other respects being the same.\n\nTo replace the CO/CP stock on the [[Edgware Road tube station (Circle, District and Hammersmith & City lines)|Edgware Road]] to [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]] section of the District line, a further eleven trains designated '''C77''' were ordered of identical layout. The 33 DM (Nos 5701-5733) and T (Nos 6701-6733) were also formed as 2 car units and could and did interrun with C69.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=117}} The first was delivered in July 1977.<ref name=Hardy/> The class received the [[British Rail Class 499|Class 499/1]] designation on [[British Rail]]'s [[TOPS]] system to operate on the Wimbledon line.<ref>LUL stock given TOPS numbers ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1145 September 1996 page 57</ref>\n\nEquipment as built included load sensing \"Metacone\" air suspension, rheostatic braking, hydraulic parking brake, pneumatic camshaft control by GEC and Brush DC motors of type LT117, with each Dm car having four motors. Air supply was by Reavell reciprocating compressors and braking equipment was by [[Westinghouse Air Brake Company|Westinghouse]]. The guard's door controls were in the driver's cab; this eased conversion to one-man operation in 1983/84, the first LU line to do so.\n\nA car was added to the C77 order to replace C69 car 5585, which had been damaged in the [[Attacks on the London Underground#1976 IRA attacks|West Ham IRA bomb attack]] in March 1976. Unit 5585-6585 became a hybrid C69/C77 unit and was selected for a trial refurbishment in 1989 at [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]'s, [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]].<ref name=Hardy/>\n\nUnit 5606\u20136606, which had been used for various equipment trials, was scrapped in December 1994. Cars 6505 and 6713 were damaged in the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]] and were scrapped above the solebar. The remains were used in the building of new cars 6606 (the second car with this number) and 6734 as C08 stock. They were paired with 5505 and 5713, renumbered 5606 and 5734 to match their partners. 5548+6548 were rebuilt in part following the bombings.\n\n== Design ==\nThe stock was made up of three two-car units, a {{convert|16.030|m|ftin|adj=on}} driving motor and a {{convert|14.970|m|ftin|adj=on}} trailer, each with four pairs of doors on each side and seating 32 people.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|pp=114-115}} The stock had a public address system and [[rheostatic brake]]s on the driving motor.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=116}}<ref name=\"RSI\"/> Although there are technical differences, units of different ages can be coupled together{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=117}} and since the 1991\u201394 refurbishment there are no visual differences.<ref name=\"RSI\">{{cite web|title=Rolling Stock Information Sheets |url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/foi/Rolling_stock_Data_Sheet_2nd_Edition.pdf |accessdate=26 November 2012 |work=London Underground |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220173000/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/foi/Rolling_stock_Data_Sheet_2nd_Edition.pdf |archivedate=20 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"TfL-Cs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx |title=Rolling Stock: C Stock |accessdate=25 November 2012 |work=Transport for London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105134748/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx |archivedate=5 November 2012 }}</ref> The stock was unpainted until refurbishment, then painted red, white and blue.<ref name=\"RSI\"/>\n\n== Refurbishment ==\nIn 1989, the hybrid C69/C77 unit 5585-6585 was chosen as the prototype unit to undergo a trial refurbishment, which was carried out by British Rail Engineering Limited's [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]]. The exterior of both cars was painted blue above the waist level and white beneath, with the driving cabs painted red. Inside, the maple wood flooring was replaced by light grey, grooved, moulded flooring, and the non-cab ends where fitted with windows, to improve visibility between cars and improve passenger safety. Trailer car 6585 underwent more substantial changes, with the transverse seating removed and replaced with longitudinal seating, and bulkheads redesigned to remove the illuminated advertisement panels.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hardy |first1=Brian |title=London Underground Rolling Stock |date=2002 |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=1-85414-263-1 |edition=15th}}</ref>\n\nThe prototype unit was displayed to the public and entered service on 22 November 1989. Following the success of the trial refurbishment, a contract was awarded to RFS Industries of [[Doncaster]] to refurbish the entire fleet.\n \n== Numbering ==\nC69 Stock DMs were numbered 5501-5606 plus trailers 6501-6606; C77 Stock 5585(2), 5701\u20135733, 6701-6733 and renumbered 5734; C08s Stock 6606(2) and 6734.\n\nAs delivered, the numbering system composed of the following:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n|-style=\"border-top:solid 6px #{{LUL color|Circle}};\"\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"|Formation\n|colspan=\"2\"|Reversible units\n!style=\"width:20em\" rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n|style=\"width:5em\"|'''5xxx'''<br />(DM)\n|style=\"width:5em\"|'''6xxx'''<br />(UT)\n|-style=\"border-top:solid 3px #{{LUL color|Circle}};\"\n!style=\"width:5em\" rowspan=\"3\"|Numbers\n!style=\"width:5em\"|C69\n|5501<br />:<br />5606\n|6501<br />:<br />6606(1)\n|\n* 5585(1) destroyed in 1976.\n* 6505 partly destroyed in 2005 - rebuilt as 6606(2)\n* 5505 renumbered 5606(2) in 2008\n|-\n!C77\n|5701<br />:<br />5733\n|6701<br />:<br />6733\n|\n* 6713 partly destroyed in 2005 - rebuilt as 6734\n* 5713 renumbered 5734 in 2008.\n|-\n!C08\n|style=\"background-color:#ccc;\"|\n|6606(2)<br />6734\n|\n|}\n* DM - Driving Motor car\n* UT - Uncoupling Trailer (non-powered) car\n\n== Withdrawal ==\nThe stock was replaced between 2012 and 2014 by S7 Stock.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/corporate/tube_upgrade_plan_timeline.pdf |title=Tube Upgrade Plan |date=February 2012 |publisher=Transport for London |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> Set 5595+6595 was cannibalised in 2011 as a trial programme, and resulted in a planned withdrawal until 2014. In July 2012 sets 5532+6532 and 5575+6575 were damaged beyond economical repair in a side-swipe at Hammersmith depot. They were sent to the Northwood sidings on 15 October 2012, and taken to [[Eastleigh Works]] to be scrapped.\n\nFinal withdrawal of the C Stock commenced on 2 January 2013, when the first full 6-car train, 5515+6515, 5519+6519 and 5732+6732, was taken to Northwood sidings and loaded on lorries to be scrapped. A withdrawal was made every week or two weeks until 2014, but because of delays to the introduction of S7 Stock owing to modifications needed to be made to the [[London Underground S7 and S8 Stock|S8 Stock]], the withdrawal process was temporarily halted.\n\nOn 26 April 2013 the process resumed, with 5528+5588+5701 being transferred to Acton Works for removal from the system. The C stock was completely withdrawn on the Circle and Hammersmith & City lines by 11 February 2014.\n\nOn 3 June 2014 the final scheduled working of C Stock on the London Underground system took place, consisting of 5533/6533+5517/6517+5592/6592. (Train 074). Unfortunately the last journey was cut short by four hours and ended at 9:30am, and the train went to Hammersmith Depot instead.\n\nA tour took place on 29 June 2014 traversing much of the mileage covered by the stock during its working life. One train (5721+5531+5578) was retained for this tour with one held as a reserve in case of breakdown (5533+5517+5592).<ref>C-Stock finally bows out with farwell tour ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' issue 752 9 July 2014 page 25</ref>\n\nThe second-last train, the reserve train for the tour (5533+5517+5592), was taken to Ealing Common Depot on 4 July 2014 and loaded onto trucks to be scrapped at [[CF Booth]], [[Rotherham]], the same place where many A Stock and C Stock trains were scrapped. The final train, the railtour train (5721+5531+5578), was taken to Ealing Common Depot on 9 July 2014 to be scrapped at Rotherham as well. Only Car 5721 was preserved at the [[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum's Acton depot]].<ref name=C5721>C Stock added to LTM collection ''[[Rail Express]]'' issue 244 September 2016 page 30</ref>\n\n=== Post-withdrawal use ===\nTransport for London has donated two C77 driving motors to educational establishments, and another from the same sub-series to the London Transport Museum: these are 5701, 5720 and 5721.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Sub-series!!Car number(s)!!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5701|| style=\"background:#ffb;\"|Donated by [[Transport for London]] to the [[Royal Greenwich UTC]] on 28 June 2013.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 2013|journal=Underground News|publisher=London Underground Railway Society|issue=620|page=439}}</ref>\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5720|| style=\"background:#bfb;\"|Static feature at a Plumcroft Primary School playground, [[Plumstead]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2014|journal=Underground News|publisher=London Underground Railway Society|issue=634|page=540}}</ref>\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5721|| style=\"background:#bfb;\"|Static exhibit at the [[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum's Acton depot]].<ref name=C5721/>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J Graeme|year=1983|title=Steam to Silver. A history of London Transport Surface Rolling Stock|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=0-904711-45-5|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121105134748/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx Archived C Stock page - Transport for London]\n* [https://www.squarewheels.org.uk/rly/stock/CsubsurfaceStock/ C69/C77 stock - SQUAREWHEELS.org.uk]\n\n{{London Underground rolling stock}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n[[Category:London Underground electric multiple units|C69 and C77 Stock]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Cammell multiple units]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1970]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox train\n|name         = London Underground C69 and C77 Stock\n|image        = High Street Kensington. 5730.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|caption      = A refurbished C Stock at [[High Street Kensington tube station|High Street Kensington]]\n|interiorimage = C Stock DM Interior.jpg\n|interiorcaption = The interior of refurbished C Stock\n|manufacturer = [[Metro-Cammell]]<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\">{{cite web|title=Rolling Stock Data Sheet, London Underground (First Edition)|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/66598/response/170252/attach/4/Rolling%20stock%20Data%20Sheet%202nd%20Edition%201.pdf|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n|factory      = [[Washwood Heath]], [[England]]<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n|service      = 28 September 1970 \u2013 29 June 2014 \n|family       =\n|refurbishment = 1991\u20131994\n|replaced     = [[London Underground O and P Stock|O and P Stock]]\n|lines        = {{ubl|[[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] (1970\u20132014)|[[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] (1970\u20132014)|[[District line|District]] ([[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]]\u2013[[Edgware Road tube station (Circle, District and Hammersmith & City lines)|Edgware Road]]) (1978\u20132014)}}\n|formation    = 2 cars per unit, 3 units per train\n|carlength    = DM {{convert|16.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<br>T {{convert|14.94|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|carbody      = Aluminium\n|trainlength  =\n|width        = {{convert|2.92|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|3.68|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|traction     = Pneumatically driven double camshaft<br>(C69: [[GEC Traction|English Electric-AEI Traction]]<br>C77: [[GEC Traction]])<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n|traction motors = LT117 DC motor<br>([[Brush Traction]])<ref name=\"wdtk-lu-1ed\" />\n| collectionmethod = [[Contact shoe]]\n|maxspeed     =\n|weight       = DM {{convert|31.70|t|LT ST|abbr=on}}<br>T {{convert|20.2|t|LT ST|abbr=on}}\n|seating      = 198 per trainset\n|capacity     = 821 per trainset\n|stocktype    = [[London Underground infrastructure#Subsurface versus deep-level tube lines|Subsurface]]\n|notes        = \n}}\n\nThe '''London Underground C69 and C77 Stock''', commonly referred to as '''C Stock''', was a type of sub-surface rolling stock used on the [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]], [[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] and [[District line|District]] lines of the [[London Underground]] between 1970 and 2014.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1968, '''C69''' stock 6-car trains were ordered from [[Metro-Cammell]] of [[Washwood Heath]] to replace [[London Underground O and P Stock|O Stock and P Stock]] on [[London Underground]]'s [[Circle line (London Underground)|Circle]] and [[Hammersmith & City line|Hammersmith & City]] lines for delivery from 1969, but trials of a four-car unit were delayed until summer 1970.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=114}} The first entered service on 28 September 1970.<ref name=Hardy>{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=Brian|title=London Underground Rolling Stock|date=1997|publisher=Capital Transport|location=Harrow|isbn=185414 193 7|pages=44\u201346|edition=14}}</ref>\n\nThe C69 stock was constructed using the then-standard form of a load-bearing aluminium underframe with a non-load-bearing body of riveted panels on aluminium framing. The high-density nature of the Circle line service meant that loading times were important; consequently all cars were fitted with four double sets of air-operated sliding doors per side. Seating was mainly transverse, and total seating capacity was 32 per car. The 106 DM cars (Nos 5501-5606) were each coupled to one of 106 T (Nos 6501-6606) forming semi-permanent two-car units, with an automatic coupler at each end. Three such units were then marshalled as six-car trains for normal service. The DM cars were slightly longer to accommodate the drivers' cabs, the saloon dimensions in all other respects being the same.\n\nTo replace the CO/CP stock on the [[Edgware Road tube station (Circle, District and Hammersmith & City lines)|Edgware Road]] to [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]] section of the District line, a further eleven trains designated '''C77''' were ordered of identical layout. The 33 DM (Nos 5701-5733) and T (Nos 6701-6733) were also formed as 2 car units and could and did interrun with C69.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=117}} The first was delivered in July 1977.<ref name=Hardy/> The class received the [[British Rail Class 499|Class 499/1]] designation on [[British Rail]]'s [[TOPS]] system to operate on the Wimbledon line.<ref>LUL stock given TOPS numbers ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1145 September 1996 page 57</ref>\n\nEquipment as built included load sensing \"Metacone\" air suspension, rheostatic braking, hydraulic parking brake, pneumatic camshaft control by GEC and Brush DC motors of type LT117, with each Dm car having four motors. Air supply was by Reavell reciprocating compressors and braking equipment was by [[Westinghouse Air Brake Company|Westinghouse]]. The guard's door controls were in the driver's cab; this eased conversion to one-man operation in 1983/84, the first LU line to do so.\n\nA car was added to the C77 order to replace C69 car 5585, which had been damaged in the [[Attacks on the London Underground#1976 IRA attacks|West Ham IRA bomb attack]] in March 1976. Unit 5585-6585 became a hybrid C69/C77 unit and was selected for a trial refurbishment in 1989 at [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]'s, [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]].<ref name=Hardy/>\n\nUnit 5606\u20136606, which had been used for various equipment trials, was scrapped in December 1994. Cars 6505 and 6713 were damaged in the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]] and were scrapped above the solebar. The remains were used in the building of new cars 6606 (the second car with this number) and 6734 as C08 stock. They were paired with 5505 and 5713, renumbered 5606 and 5734 to match their partners. 5548+6548 were rebuilt in part following the bombings.\n\n== Design ==\nThe stock was made up of three two-car units, a {{convert|16.030|m|ftin|adj=on}} driving motor and a {{convert|14.970|m|ftin|adj=on}} trailer, each with four pairs of doors on each side and seating 32 people.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|pp=114-115}} The stock had a public address system and [[rheostatic brake]]s on the driving motor.{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=116}}<ref name=\"RSI\"/> Although there are technical differences, units of different ages can be coupled together{{sfn|Bruce|1983|p=117}} and since the 1991\u201394 refurbishment there are no visual differences.<ref name=\"RSI\">{{cite web|title=Rolling Stock Information Sheets |url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/foi/Rolling_stock_Data_Sheet_2nd_Edition.pdf |accessdate=26 November 2012 |work=London Underground |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220173000/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/foi/Rolling_stock_Data_Sheet_2nd_Edition.pdf |archivedate=20 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"TfL-Cs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx |title=Rolling Stock: C Stock |accessdate=25 November 2012 |work=Transport for London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105134748/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx |archivedate=5 November 2012 }}</ref> The stock was unpainted until refurbishment, then painted red, white and blue.<ref name=\"RSI\"/>\n\n== Refurbishment ==\nIn 1989, the hybrid C69/C77 unit 5585-6585 was chosen as the prototype unit to undergo a trial refurbishment, which was carried out by British Rail Engineering Limited's [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]]. The exterior of both cars was painted blue above the waist level and white beneath, with the driving cabs painted red. Inside, the maple wood flooring was replaced by light grey, grooved, moulded flooring, and the non-cab ends where fitted with windows, to improve visibility between cars and improve passenger safety. Trailer car 6585 underwent more substantial changes, with the transverse seating removed and replaced with longitudinal seating, and bulkheads redesigned to remove the illuminated advertisement panels.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hardy |first1=Brian |title=London Underground Rolling Stock |date=2002 |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=1-85414-263-1 |edition=15th}}</ref>\n\nThe prototype unit was displayed to the public and entered service on 22 November 1989. Following the success of the trial refurbishment, a contract was awarded to RFS Industries of [[Doncaster]] to refurbish the entire fleet.\n \n== Numbering ==\nC69 Stock DMs were numbered 5501-5606 plus trailers 6501-6606; C77 Stock 5585(2), 5701\u20135733, 6701-6733 and renumbered 5734; C08s Stock 6606(2) and 6734.\n\nAs delivered, the numbering system composed of the following:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n|-style=\"border-top:solid 6px #{{LUL color|Circle}};\"\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"|Formation\n|colspan=\"2\"|Reversible units\n!style=\"width:20em\" rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n|style=\"width:5em\"|'''5xxx'''<br />(DM)\n|style=\"width:5em\"|'''6xxx'''<br />(UT)\n|-style=\"border-top:solid 3px #{{LUL color|Circle}};\"\n!style=\"width:5em\" rowspan=\"3\"|Numbers\n!style=\"width:5em\"|C69\n|5501<br />:<br />5606\n|6501<br />:<br />6606(1)\n|\n* 5585(1) destroyed in 1975.\n* 5505 partly destroyed in 2005 - rebuilt as 5606(2)\n* 6505 renumbered 6606(2) in 2008\n|-\n!C77\n|5701<br />:<br />5733\n|6701<br />:<br />6733\n|\n* 6713 partly destroyed in 2005 - rebuilt as 6734\n* 5713 renumbered 5734 in 2008.\n|-\n!C08\n|style=\"background-color:#ccc;\"|\n|6606(2)<br />6734\n|\n|}\n* DM - Driving Motor car\n* UT - Uncoupling Trailer (non-powered) car\n\n== Withdrawal ==\nThe stock was replaced between 2012 and 2014 by S7 Stock.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/corporate/tube_upgrade_plan_timeline.pdf |title=Tube Upgrade Plan |date=February 2012 |publisher=Transport for London |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> Set 5595+6595 was cannibalised in 2011 as a trial programme, and resulted in a planned withdrawal until 2014. In July 2012 sets 5532+6532 and 5575+6575 were damaged beyond economical repair in a side-swipe at Hammersmith depot. They were sent to the Northwood sidings on 15 October 2012, and taken to [[Eastleigh Works]] to be scrapped.\n\nFinal withdrawal of the C Stock commenced on 2 January 2013, when the first full 6-car train, 5515+6515, 5519+6519 and 5732+6732, was taken to Northwood sidings and loaded on lorries to be scrapped. A withdrawal was made every week or two weeks until 2014, but because of delays to the introduction of S7 Stock owing to modifications needed to be made to the [[London Underground S7 and S8 Stock|S8 Stock]], the withdrawal process was temporarily halted.\n\nOn 26 April 2013 the process resumed, with 5528+5588+5701 being transferred to Acton Works for removal from the system. The C stock was completely withdrawn on the Circle and Hammersmith & City lines by 11 February 2014.\n\nOn 3 June 2014 the final scheduled working of C Stock on the London Underground system took place, consisting of 5533/6533+5517/6517+5592/6592. (Train 074). Unfortunately the last journey was cut short by four hours and ended at 9:30am, and the train went to Hammersmith Depot instead.\n\nA tour took place on 29 June 2014 traversing much of the mileage covered by the stock during its working life. One train (5721+5531+5578) was retained for this tour with one held as a reserve in case of breakdown (5533+5517+5592).<ref>C-Stock finally bows out with farwell tour ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' issue 752 9 July 2014 page 25</ref>\n\nThe second-last train, the reserve train for the tour (5533+5517+5592), was taken to Ealing Common Depot on 4 July 2014 and loaded onto trucks to be scrapped at [[CF Booth]], [[Rotherham]], the same place where many A Stock and C Stock trains were scrapped. The final train, the railtour train (5721+5531+5578), was taken to Ealing Common Depot on 9 July 2014 to be scrapped at Rotherham as well. Only Car 5721 was preserved at the [[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum's Acton depot]].<ref name=C5721>C Stock added to LTM collection ''[[Rail Express]]'' issue 244 September 2016 page 30</ref>\n\n=== Post-withdrawal use ===\nTransport for London has donated two C77 driving motors to educational establishments, and another from the same sub-series to the London Transport Museum: these are 5701, 5720 and 5721.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Sub-series!!Car number(s)!!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5701|| style=\"background:#ffb;\"|Donated by [[Transport for London]] to the [[Royal Greenwich UTC]] on 28 June 2013.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 2013|journal=Underground News|publisher=London Underground Railway Society|issue=620|page=439}}</ref>\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5720|| style=\"background:#bfb;\"|Static feature at a Plumcroft Primary School playground, [[Plumstead]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2014|journal=Underground News|publisher=London Underground Railway Society|issue=634|page=540}}</ref>\n|-\n|C77 Stock||5721|| style=\"background:#bfb;\"|Static exhibit at the [[London Transport Museum#The depot (Acton)|London Transport Museum's Acton depot]].<ref name=C5721/>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J Graeme|year=1983|title=Steam to Silver. A history of London Transport Surface Rolling Stock|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=0-904711-45-5|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121105134748/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/corporate/modesoftransport/londonunderground/rollingstock/1616.aspx Archived C Stock page - Transport for London]\n* [https://www.squarewheels.org.uk/rly/stock/CsubsurfaceStock/ C69/C77 stock - SQUAREWHEELS.org.uk]\n\n{{London Underground rolling stock}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n[[Category:London Underground electric multiple units|C69 and C77 Stock]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Cammell multiple units]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1970]]\n", "name_user": "C2A", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNumbering:some corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Underground_C69_and_C77_Stock"}
{"title_page": "The Longest Night (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Longest Night\n| image          = The Longest Night (2019 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Gabriela Calvache]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[No\u00eblle Sch\u00f6nwald]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2019|3|9|[[South by Southwest|SXSW]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Ecuador\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Longest Night''''' ({{lang-es|'''La mala noche'''}}) is a 2019 Ecuadorian [[drama film]] directed by [[Gabriela Calvache]]. It was selected as the Ecuadorian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]] at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], but it was not nominated.<ref name=\"Ecuador\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eltelegrafo.com.ec/noticias/cultura/10/la-mala-noche-premios-oscar-goya |title=''La mala noche'' representa a Ecuador para postular a premios Oscar y Goya |work=El Telegrafo |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA prostitute exploited by a mafia boss tries to break free and pursue justice.<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite web|url=https://schedule.sxsw.com/2019/films/2008876 |title=SXSW Schedule: La Mala Noche |work=SXSW |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[No\u00eblle Sch\u00f6nwald]] as Dana\n* [[Cristian Mercado]] as Juli\u00e1n\n* [[Jaime Tamariz]] as Nelson\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 92nd Academy Awards for Best International Feature Film]]\n* [[List of Ecuadorian submissions for the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|6857084|The Longest Night}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Longest Night, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\